05854nam a22007215i 9780773550810DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735508107 a10.1515/97807735508102doi  a(DE-B1597)657549  a(OCoLC)972182021  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBH 7aART0150002bisacsh04a701/.18223  aLH 62000qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/94235:00aNarratives Unfolding :bNational Art Histories in an Unfinished World /ced. by Martha Langford. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b100 colour photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Beaverbrook Canadian Foundation Studies in Art History ;v2200tFront Matter -- tcontents -- tillustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPlaying Out the “Differences” in “Turkish” Art-Historical Narratives -- tRace, Irishness, and Art History -- tProblems of Translation -- tSome Notes on Applying Postcolonial Methodologies to Architectural History Research in Israel/Palestine -- t“Draw Me a Sheep!” -- tHistorical Archives and Contemporary Art -- tDalriada, the Lordship of the Isles, and the Northern Rim -- tNew Maps for Networks -- tHitching a Ride -- tMigratory Affiliations -- tMaraya’s Sisyphean Cart -- tUrban Art Histories (in Canada) -- tA Stranger in New York -- tMending Walls -- tEmbodying Sovereignty -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSomewhere between global and local, the nation still lingers as a concept. National art histories continue to be written – some for the first time – while innovative methods and practices redraw the boundaries of these imagined communities. Narratives Unfolding considers the mobility of ideas, transnationalism, and entangled histories in essays that define new ways to see national art in ever-changing nations. Examining works that were designed to reclaim or rethink issues of territory and dispossession, home and exile, contributors to this volume demonstrate that the writing of national art histories is a vital project for intergenerational exchange of knowledge and its visual formations. Essays showcase revealing moments of modern and contemporary art history in Canada, Egypt, Iceland, India, Ireland, Israel/Palestine, Romania, Scotland, Turkey, and the United Arab Emirates, paying particular attention to the agency of institutions such as archives, art galleries, milestone exhibitions, and artist retreats. Old and emergent art cities, including Cairo, Dubai, New York, and Vancouver, are also examined in light of avant-gardism, cosmopolitanism, and migration. Narratives Unfolding is both a survey of current art historical approaches and their connection to the source: art-making and art experience happening somewhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtxHistoriography. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh1 aBarber, Fionna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeattie, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Asher Gitler, Inbal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlair, Lindsay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl-Sheikh, Tammer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIlea, Corina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangford, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangford, Martha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLyons, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab